RABIES, HUMAN - INDONESIA (18): (BALI)
**************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Wed 24 Nov 2010
Source: Malay Peninsula Standard, via Bali Animal Welfare Society
[abbreviated, edited]


Rabid dogs kill 2 people
------------------------
A 13 year old boy from Banjar Gentong, Tegallalang, died with rabies at
Sanglah Hospital on Tue 23 Nov 20010. He was a 6th grade student in
Tegallalang and had been bitten by a dog 3 months ago during a sports
meeting on 17 Aug 2010. The boy's father said that his son is the 2nd
rabies victim in Gentong, the 1st being a 35 year old man. The head of
Gentong Banjar has been requested by the Animal Husbandry Agency to
eliminate stray dogs in Banjar Gentong. This will be carried out on
Wednesday [24 Nov 2010].

Meanwhile, Dr IGB Ken Wirasandi, secretary of the Rabies Control Team of
Sanglah Hospital, stated after reviewing the symptoms that the boy was
rabies-positive. However, he regretted that most rabies victims never
received post exposure vaccination or had their wounds treated. He added
also that since end of 2008 until 2010 the Sanglah Hospital has treated 123
suspect rabies victims. Of these 75, including the latest victim, have
died. [Presumably the survivors had not in fact contracted rabies virus
infection. - Mod.CP]

As of yesterday [23 Nov 2010], 2 more suspect rabies patients are still
being treated at Nusa Indah Hospital.

A patient treated initially at Sanjiwani Hospital, has been transferred to
Sanglah hospital as his condition worsened. The patient stated that he had
not been bitten by a dog. According to one of his family members, in fact
the victim had been bitten by a rat in his own home. 3 days ago the patient
had fallen from his motorbike and subsequently suffered seizures with
symptoms similar to rabies. Accordingly, he was rushed to Sanjiwani Hospital.

--
communicated by:
Merritt Clifton
Editor, Animal People
