[Merritt Clifton has appended the following comments regarding the report
above.

The precise number of rabies fatalities in Bali remains uncertain. Only 2
days earlier the Malay Peninsula Standard reported that, "The death toll
for 'suspected' rabies is now 106 people, 46 of whom were rabies positive
based on laboratory test results." I have now logged 79 rabies deaths by
name, age of victim, and place, but every recent media report places the
total number of deaths as upward of 100, and as many as 130 deaths are now
possible (as previously enumerated on ProMED-mail).

Rats are rarely a vector for rabies virus because they die too rapidly
after becoming infected. But in places where dogs are the major form of rat
control and dogs have been exterminated, the likelihood of rats biting
people is increased, not least because rats overpopulate their most favored
habitat and expand into places where they have previously been checked by
dogs -- like houses that are more-or-less open to the wildlife and the
elements. [The diagnosis in the case of this patient remains tentative. -
Mod.CP]

The Bali Animal Welfare Association is reportedly going great guns on their
vaccination program, funded by the World Society for the Protection of
Animals, but there have been several strategic misunderstandings occasioned
by different understandings of relevant terminology. For example, I was
called upon a couple of weeks ago to explain to some of the participants
the difference between "ring vaccination" (vaccinating around an outbreak)
and "circle vaccination" (vaccinating in the outbreak area and surrounding
radius), since in literal translation "ring" and "circle" are exactly the
same thing. Some of the other points of confusion include the perennial
mix-up of "shot" meaning inoculation, with "shot" meaning gunshot. My own
perspective is that anyone calling a vaccination a shot should be
vaccinated. - MC

A map of the island of Bali can be accessed at
<http://www.baliguide.com/bali_map.html>. The HealthMap/ProMED-mail
interactive map of Indonesia can be found at <http://healthmap.org/r/0hez>.
- Mod.CP]
